    <title>Combined summary - Core Devs : can you share your thoughts about all BIPs on this website ?</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T20:29:22.610037+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010394.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Nicolas Dorier, a member of the Bitcoin development community, proposed a website where developers can express their opinions on various proposals in one place. The website aims to help the community and encourage more people to contribute to the project. Users can fill out whether they approve or not, and give comments with HTML accepted, allowing for linking. Some members suggested adding more core developers and experts like Nick Szabo, Meni Rosenfeld, Charlie Lee, and Mike Hearn to the website. The website also includes a "Technical Opinion" column for developers to express their opinions on various proposals in one place. In addition, discussions among members touched on improving the readability of the website and addressing concerns about getting PGP keys from contributors who had them scattered all over the place. Other suggestions included creating an information site to summarize the differences between current outstanding BIPs and including supporting and counter statements regarding these BIPs on the site. Overall, the website serves as a valuable tool for the community to educate themselves and link their thoughts about various BIPs.The conversation revolves around the implications of capping the block size of Bitcoin at 1 MB. The writer argues that it restricts the number of active users and ultimately leads to the fall of Rome. The other person in the conversation disagrees with this opinion and thinks that a relative tight block size could not harm Bitcoin middle-term. Capping the block size is limiting the number of active users to around 100,000 people transacting twice a day on blockchain, which restricts new users from joining and freezes the economic incentive to mine, hurting the price of Bitcoin and threatening its position as the leading cryptocurrency. Controlled growth through the implementation of BIP101 is necessary for the continued success of the protocol, and other competing protocols could gain an advantage if Bitcoin's growth is stalled.There are ongoing discussions about improving the website's readability and adding more developers, big miners, and other important figures. Nicolas Dorier agreed to add important developers, big miners, or other proposals that he missed like Adam Back, Mark Friedenbach, Jorge Timons, Peter Todd, and thebluematt.In response to the issue of block size, Gregory Maxwell suggests that analysis and options should be laid out before making any decisions on blocksize, and developers should explain their threat models and what should be at the root of their thinking about the block size. A public release has revealed that a group has agreed that an increase in blocksize is necessary, but opposed the original suggestion of 20mb and instead suggested 8mb as it is more technically reasonable. Yifu Guo stated that not increasing the blocksize is not an option. However, he also believes that increasing the block size will only eliminate the pressure to find long-term solutions and may not turn out as expected. He expressed doubt about the success of a 20-year plan and suggested that clearing away the auto-increase could be the best solution at present.There are concerns about the influence of the Chinese state on Chinese mining and how it might cause Chinese miners to adopt XT due to state pressure. It is recommended that people do not use XT and work to develop consensus on an alternative proposal that increases block size such as BIP 100. Nicolas Dorier created a website that displays charts of user's approvals for various BIPs, allowing individuals to fill in whether they approve or not and leave comments. The site also provides links to BTC Talk topic and Github. One user expressed concern that this approach could lead to premature judgments before proper analysis and options are laid out, potentially negating future work on BIPs that are still in development or have yet to be proposed. However, the goal of the website is not to make decisions but rather to provide a way for the community to see the pros and cons of various proposals in one place. The debate on bitcoin block size increase continues with a recent tweet from Antpool stating that they support increasing the block size and would be prepared to switch to XT if a majority had switched. However, many people are supportive of increasing the block size but have spent much time calling attention to the many problems of XT. People should attend conferences and contribute to the discussion.</summary>
